\fBNote\fP
.RS 4
Example of using the logging wrapper! For some cases, I thought would be most common, there are definitions/macros (OUTPUT, LOG_INFO, LOG_WARNING, LOG_ERROR, LOG_DEBUG) that can be used\&. For other cases, the utils::log function can be used directly\&. Possibilitys:
.IP "\(bu" 2
utils::log(bool verbose = false) - Logs INFO, verbose can be set to true
.IP "\(bu" 2
utils::log(LogLevel level) - Logs the given level, verbose is false, however only INFO can be verbose anyway, as all other always print to the console
.IP "\(bu" 2
utils::log(comst std::string &prefix, bool verbose = false) - Logs INFO, with a custom prefix, verbose can be set to true
.IP "\(bu" 2
utils::log(const std::string &prefix, LogLevel level, bool verbose = false) - Logs the given level, with a custom prefix, verbose can be set to true
.PP
.RE
.PP
All of the above return a std::ostream, so you can use it like e\&.g\&. a normal std::cout!
